  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legal (i.e., \"clean\") by disguising the true origin of the funds. This is typically done through a series of complex transactions or activities that make it difficult to trace the money back to its illegal source.\n\nCountries have established laws and regulations to combat money laundering, often requiring financial institutions and other entities to report suspicious activities and implement robust anti-money laundering (AML) programs. Penalties for money laundering can include significant fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) is an international body that sets standards and promotes effective implementation of legal, regulatory, and operational measures for combating money laundering, terrorist financing, and other related threats to the integrity of the international financial system.",
